<br>
I agree, and but also feel, why should the try and make every new expansion suitable for every kind of player? Personally, that seems like a nightmare to try and figure out.<br>
<br>
Which parts would be for casual encounters, which for raids? How do you keep one from spilling over into another? Should the rewards for the casual areas be as good as the rewards from the raid intesive areas? If the rewards are, what's the point of ever going to the raid intesive encounters. If the rewards for the casual areas suck, no one will do them. <br>
<br>
We also have to remember, that the makers of the game have changed. And with new people, come new ideas, new directions. Personally, I like alot of the things Sony has done. Even if one of them was making porting partially useless. They realized that most of thier players aren't druids or wizards, without the ability to port themselves. Traveling was just a stupid time suck for most people in the game. While I have thought that the plane of knowledge should be accessable to players level 25 and up, oh well. <br>
<br>
Verant always designed content to go with what they invisioned the game. Which was pretty limited. Start off alone, learn how to group, learn how to raid, join a guild, take down the end boss mob of the game. Repeat as a different class. Sony is at least adding content that covers everything. <br>
<br>
PoP is meant for uber guilds that raid alot. LoY was a great expantion in my mind. Each zone could be done, for the most part, with just a group. The rewards were decent to good. And over all, it felt very complete. Now LDoN is for the casual player. Perfect. At least Sony is acknowledging those players, something Verant never seemed to want to do.<br>
<br>
Verants idea of keeping customers always seemed to invovle making everything time consumming, hard, drawn out and in some cases, plain stupid. There are quests you can do starting at level one, but can't be finished till level 45 and they suck. <br>
<br>
Sony seems to at least want to make it fun for both hardcore players, and the casual player. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=faramir42>Faramir42</A> at: 6/15/03 9:28 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dmitrythewizzy>Dmitry the Wizzy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist<br>The People's Gnome</span><br>  Posts: 1905<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/15/03 8:35 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: But why should they?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Theres no mixing, so all PoP encounters are largely the same, in as much as all Luclin and Velious encounters were the same.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
